727326f-a.folder: Main Street & Northern Boulevard, Queens, NY
727326f-a.text:
Main Street, west side, south of Northern Boulevard to Thirty-ninth Ave. St. George's Protestant Episcopal Church is in the background on Thirty-ninth Ave. The brick front structure next to the one bearing the sign plate W. Follet was the parsonage of this church and was occupied by the Rev. Barzillai from 1809-1820. It is now designated Nos. 37-39 Main Street.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

727327f-a.folder: Main Street & Northern Boulevard, Queens, NY
727327f-a.text:
Main St., (old Nos. 11,13,15) west side, south of Northern Boulevard. Caleb W. Smith, left foreground, lived here in 1870. He operated a candy store. Geo Barron occupied the center house. He was a friend of Smith's. Mr. Barron kept a clothing store here. He died in this small house in 1926. Woolworth store occupies the site in 1922.
1922
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

727330f-a.folder: Main Street & Northern Boulevard, Queens, NY
727330f-a.text:
Main Street (foreground), at the S.E. corner of Northern Boulevard, showing the Fountain House. In 1830 Benj. F. Lowerre, later Charles F. Lowerre, and in 1873 the C.P. Lowerre Estate owned this tavern. Eugene L. Armbruster states that Jacob F. Haubeil was long the owner of this tavern. He lived at 136 Broadway and never lived in the Fountain House. His pater operated, built, and owned the Washington Hotel in 1855. The building in this view does not appear in the Queens Atlas of 1926.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

727563f-a.folder: Northern Boulevard & Main Street, Queens, NY
727563f-a.text:
Northern Boulevard, north side, at and adjoining the N.W. corner of Main Street (left), showing a 3½ story frame structure occupied by the Underhills who conducted a grocery from 1870 to 1890. It was a boarding house and postoffice in 1830. The Flushing Journal was located for fifty years next to the Grocery. In the 1926 Queens Atlas the corner structure shows as brick or stucco. It may still be the old structure remodeled.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

727568f-a.folder: Northern Boulevard & Main Street, Queens, NY
727568f-a.text:
Northern Boulevard, south side, east of Main Street, showing three views (from three different angles) of the Quaker Meeting House of Flushing, built in 1694. The Quakers held their first annual meeting here on May 30th, 1696. The British, during the Revolution, used the structure as a barrack, hospital, prison and bay magazine.
View 1: 1922
Views 2,3: July, 1925
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

727569f-a.folder: Northern Boulevard & Main Street, Queens, NY
727569f-a.text:
Northern Boulevard, south side, east of Main St., showing in a set of 4 views the rear and side of the Quaker Meeting house, erected in 1694. The lock on the inside is encased in an oak block about 8"x14"x1 ½" and is fastened by hand made screws. It is the original lock. The wood burning stoves, found still in service here, were imported from England over two hundred years ago. The heat is distributed by pipes extending along the ceiling.
July 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

727570f-a.folder: Northern Boulevard & Main Street, Queens, NY
727570f-a.text:
orthern Boulevard, south side, east of Main St., showing in a set of three views the Quaker Meeting House of Flushing. The land upon which this building was erected;from 1694-57was puchased in 1692 for the sum of f 40. On May 30, 1696 their first annual meeting was held here. This building was shingled plastered, and repaired in 1704. The Quaker records state1 A new building was erected in 1719 near the old one and was 65'x42' in size. This refers probably to an addition. In 1763, the gallery was taken out and a floor was laid, making it a two story structure. The British used the structure as a barrack, hospital, prison, and bay magazine; being restored to the original owner in 1783. The Orthodox Quakers built a meeting house east of the old (Hicksite), meeting house in the 183O's. The picket fence surrounding this building as removed in 1911, and the
Orthodox Meeting House in 1909
1922
View 2: March 1924.
View 3: July 1925.

727575f-a.folder: Northern Boulevard & Main Street, Queens, NY
727575f-a.text:
Northern Boulevard, south side, east from Main Street. On the left is a small public park which separates the boulevard in twain. The second house from the right is the I. Frost house of 1873, and beyond it is the old Quaker Meeting House. View 2 shows the same area some years later. vast changes have taken place here. The former country-like atmosphere has change into one of a thriving business district.
View 1: Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  1922
View 2: P.L. Sperr  May 27, 1939
